  abstract  = {Determining the soundscape quality of a location is typically labor-intensive, since actual volunteers must be recruited to make the subjective evaluations. To reduce the reliance on subjective evaluations, psychoacoustic parameters and objective measurements of the acoustic environment have traditionally been used to model perceptual attributes of soundscapes and predict soundscape quality. However, existing models tend to generalize sub-optimally and neglect the listener context in the definition of a soundscape according to ISO/TS 12913-1:2014. Deep neural network (DNN) architectures with spectrogram-based inputs have recently been shown to be highly generalizable to a variety of audio detection and classification problems, and can easily be modified to accept multi-modal inputs. Hence, we hypothesize that DNNs can be robust predictive models for soundscapes that account for both the acoustic environment and listener context, and we present a preliminary study of this with bird songs as acoustic stimuli. Participants rated the stimuli based on their pleasantness and eventfulness, and a DNN was then trained to predict the ratings a participant gave a particular soundscape, given the acoustic environment and demographic information of the participant. The DNN performance was finally evaluated based on standard metrics.},
